    <!-- AFFILIATE DISCLAIMER -->
    <AffiliateDisclaimer />

    <!-- INTRO SECTION -->
    <h2 id="why-weight-loss-gummies">Weight Loss Gummies: Separating Science from Marketing Hype</h2>

    <p>Americans spend over $2.1 billion annually on weight loss supplements, yet the vast majority of products on the market fail to deliver meaningful results. The core problem is not that metabolic-support ingredients do not work — several have genuine clinical evidence behind them — but that most supplements either underdose the active compounds or rely on ingredients with no human trial data at all. Weight loss gummies add another layer of complexity: fitting clinically effective doses into a small, palatable gummy is a formulation challenge that many brands solve by simply using less active ingredient.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">$2.1B</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">spent annually on weight loss supplements in the US alone, yet fewer than 15% of products contain clinically studied ingredients at doses matching published research. The gap between marketing claims and formulation reality is wider in the weight loss category than in any other supplement segment.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The ingredients with the strongest clinical evidence for metabolic support include apple cider vinegar (acetic acid), green tea catechins (EGCG), chromium picolinate, and B-vitamins. Each works through a different mechanism — appetite modulation, thermogenesis, blood sugar regulation, and energy metabolism respectively — and none produces dramatic results in isolation. The most effective approach combines evidence-backed supplementation with a calorie-conscious diet and regular physical activity.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="flask" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Apple Cider Vinegar</h4>
        <p>Acetic acid modulates appetite signaling and may slow gastric emptying, increasing satiety. A 2018 study showed ACV consumption reduced body weight and visceral fat over 12 weeks in a calorie-restricted diet context.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="leaf" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Green Tea Extract (EGCG)</h4>
        <p>Epigallocatechin gallate (EGCG) enhances thermogenesis and fat oxidation. Meta-analyses suggest 250-500mg EGCG daily can increase energy expenditure by 80-100 calories per day, primarily from fat metabolism.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="scale" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Chromium Picolinate</h4>
        <p>Improves insulin sensitivity and glucose uptake into cells. A 2019 meta-analysis of 21 RCTs found chromium supplementation significantly reduced body weight and BMI, with the strongest effects in overweight individuals.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="zap" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>B-Vitamin Complex</h4>
        <p>B6, B12, and folate are essential cofactors in energy metabolism pathways. Deficiency impairs fat and carbohydrate metabolism, making adequate B-vitamin status a prerequisite for efficient calorie utilization.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>A 2018 study in the <em>Journal of Functional Foods</em> found that participants consuming <strong>15mL of apple cider vinegar daily for 12 weeks</strong> showed significant reductions in body weight (-1.7kg), BMI, waist circumference, and visceral fat area compared to placebo — when combined with a 250-calorie daily deficit. The acetic acid is the active compound, and gummy forms typically deliver one-third to one-half the dose used in the study.</p>
      <cite>Journal of Functional Foods, 2018 — Randomized controlled trial, 39 participants</cite>
    </div>

    <!-- PRODUCT 1 — GOLI ACV + WEIGHT -->
