    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Weight Loss Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do weight loss gummies actually work?</summary>
      <p>Weight loss gummies can support fat metabolism when they contain clinically studied ingredients at effective doses, but they are not magic pills. Ingredients like apple cider vinegar, green tea extract (EGCG), and B-vitamins have published research supporting modest metabolic benefits. A 2018 study in the <em>Journal of Functional Foods</em> found that daily ACV consumption reduced body weight and visceral fat over 12 weeks when combined with a calorie deficit. No gummy replaces diet and exercise — they are best viewed as a complementary tool within a comprehensive weight management program.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How long does it take to see results from weight loss gummies?</summary>
      <p>Most clinical studies on weight-loss-supporting ingredients show measurable effects after 8-12 weeks of consistent daily use combined with a balanced diet and regular physical activity. Green tea extract studies typically report significant fat oxidation increases within 4-8 weeks. ACV studies show body composition changes at the 12-week mark. Individual results vary based on starting weight, diet quality, exercise frequency, sleep habits, and metabolic rate.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What ingredients should I look for in weight loss gummies?</summary>
      <p>The most evidence-backed ingredients include apple cider vinegar (500mg+ acetic acid per serving), green tea extract standardized to EGCG (250-500mg), chromium picolinate (200-1000mcg), and B-vitamins (B6 and B12) for energy metabolism. Avoid products with proprietary blends that hide individual ingredient doses, and be skeptical of any product claiming dramatic weight loss without diet and exercise changes.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are weight loss gummies safe?</summary>
      <p>Most weight loss gummies containing ACV, green tea extract, and B-vitamins are generally safe for healthy adults at recommended doses. However, green tea extract above 800mg EGCG daily has been associated with liver toxicity in rare cases. Stimulant-containing gummies should be limited per FDA guidance (400mg caffeine daily from all sources). Individuals with thyroid disorders, diabetes, or those taking blood thinners should consult a physician before starting any weight management supplement. Pregnant and nursing women should avoid weight loss supplements entirely.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can I take weight loss gummies with other supplements?</summary>
      <p>In most cases yes, but be mindful of ingredient overlap. If your weight loss gummy contains caffeine or green tea extract and you also take a pre-workout supplement, you could exceed safe caffeine limits. ACV gummies can interact with diuretics and insulin by affecting potassium levels and blood sugar. Chromium may enhance the effect of diabetes medications, potentially causing hypoglycemia. Catalog all active ingredients across your supplement stack and check for duplications.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between ACV gummies and ACV liquid?</summary>
      <p>Liquid ACV delivers approximately 750-1500mg of acetic acid per tablespoon and costs significantly less per serving than gummies. ACV gummies typically provide 500mg of ACV per serving, yielding roughly 250mg of acetic acid — one-third to one-sixth the amount in liquid. The advantage of gummies is taste, convenience, and protection of tooth enamel which liquid ACV can erode. If maximum acetic acid intake is the priority, liquid wins. If compliance and dental health matter more, gummies are a reasonable alternative.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do weight loss gummies work without exercise?</summary>
      <p>Weight loss gummies may provide modest metabolic support without exercise, but the effect is minimal. A 2009 study in the <em>Journal of Nutrition</em> found that green tea catechins combined with moderate exercise produced greater abdominal fat loss than exercise alone. Without a calorie deficit, no supplement produces meaningful weight loss. Gummies should be viewed as a 5-10% enhancement to an existing healthy lifestyle, not a substitute for it.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much apple cider vinegar is in weight loss gummies?</summary>
      <p>Most ACV gummies contain 500-1000mg of apple cider vinegar per serving, yielding approximately 250-500mg of acetic acid. Clinical studies showing body composition improvements used 15-30mL of liquid ACV daily (750-1500mg acetic acid). Most ACV gummies deliver roughly one-third to two-thirds of the clinically studied dose. Look for gummies with at least 500mg ACV per serving and take the full recommended serving consistently.</p>
    </details>

